</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Restricted Cash
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash and cash equivalents that are restricted as to withdrawal or are under the terms
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of use for current operations
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	are included in the restricted balance on the balance sheet.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Cash and cash equivalents that are restricted as to withdrawal and designated for expenditure in the construction of noncurrent assets are included in long-term restricted cash on the balance sheet.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Trade Receivables
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Trade receivables are carried at original invoice amount less an estimate made for doubtful accounts. Management determines the allowance for doubtful accounts on a specific identification basis as well as by using historical experience applied to an aging of accounts. Trade receivables are written off when deemed uncollectible. Recoveries of trade receivables previously written off are recorded when received. The allowance for doubtful accounts was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$70,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$113,500
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively. The Company does not accrue interest on accounts receivable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Inventories
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Inventories are stated at the lower of cost (determined using the weighted average cost method) or market. Inventories consist primarily of merchandise held for sale. Inventories were comprised of the following at December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company provides provisions for losses related to shrinkage and other amounts that are not otherwise expected to be fully recoverable. These provisions are calculated based on historical shrinkage, selling price, margin and current business trends.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;The provision for losses related to shrinkage and other amounts was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$163,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$337,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Income Taxes
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company recognizes deferred tax liabilities and assets for the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements or tax returns. Deferred tax liabilities and assets are determined based on the difference between the financial statement basis and tax basis of assets and liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse. The Company estimates the degree to which tax assets and credit carry forwards will result in a benefit based on expected profitability by tax jurisdiction. A valuation allowance for such tax assets and loss carry forwards is provided when it is determined to be more likely than not that the benefit of such deferred tax asset will not be realized in future periods. If it becomes more likely than not that a tax asset will be used, the related valuation allowance on such assets would be reduced.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company records interest and penalties&nbsp;relating to uncertain tax positions&nbsp;in income tax expense. As of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, the Company has not recognized any liabilities for uncertain tax positions nor has the Company accrued interest and penalties related to uncertain tax positions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Revenue Recognition
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company recognizes sales at the time that the customer takes possession of the merchandise or when final delivery of the product has occurred. The Company recognizes service revenue, which consists primarily of freight charges for home delivery, when the service has been rendered. The Company is required to charge and collect sales and other taxes on sales to&nbsp;the Company's&nbsp;customers and remit these taxes back to government authorities. Total revenues do not include sales tax because the Company is&nbsp;a pass-through conduit for collecting and remitting sales tax. Sales are reduced by an allowance for anticipated sales returns that the Company estimates based on historical returns. The process to establish a sales return reserve contains uncertainties because it requires management to make assumptions and to apply judgment to estimate future returns and exchanges. The customer may receive a refund or exchange the original product for a replacement of equal or similar quality for a period of six months from the time of original purchase. Products received back under this policy are reconditioned pursuant to state laws and resold.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	67

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	The Company r
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	ecognizes expense for its stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	based compensation based on the fair value of the awards that are granted. Compensation expense is recognized
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period, net of actual forfeitures
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.&nbsp;The Company may issue incentive awards in the form of stock options, restricted stock awards and other equity awards to employees and non-employee directors.&nbsp;Compensation cost is recognized ratably over the requisite serv
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	ice period of the related stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	based compensation award.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Concentration of Risk
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Financial instruments that potentially subject the Company to concentrations of credit risk consist principally of cash and cash equivalents and bank deposits. By their nature, all such instruments involve risks including credit risks of non-performance by counterparties. A substantial portion of the Company's cash and cash equivalents and bank deposits are invested with banks with high investment grade credit ratings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Tile Shop Holdings, Inc. and Subsidiaries
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Segments
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company&#x2019;s operations consist primarily of retail sales of manufactured and natural stone tiles, setting and maintenance materials, and related accessories in stores located in the United States and through its website. The Company&#x2019;s chief operating decision maker only reviews the consolidated results of the Company and accordingly, the Company has concluded it has one reportable segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Advertising Costs
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Advertising costs were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$6.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$6.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$5.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, for the years ended December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively, and are included in selling, general and administrative expenses in the consolidated statements of operations. The Company&#x2019;s advertising consists primarily of digital media, direct marketing, event
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and traditional print media that is expensed at the time the media is distributed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Pre-opening
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	C
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	osts
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company&#x2019;s pre-opening costs are those typically associated with the opening of a new store and generally include rent expense, payroll costs and promotional costs. The Company expenses pre-opening costs as incurred which are recorded in selling, general and administrative expenses. During the years ended December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, the Company reported pre-opening costs of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$1.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Property, Plant and Equipment
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Property, plant equipment and leasehold improvements are recorded at cost. Improvements are capitalized while repairs and maintenance costs are charged to selling, general and administrative expenses when incurred. Property, plant and equipment are depreciated or amortized using the straight-line method over each asset&#x2019;s estimated useful life. Leasehold improvements and fixtures at leased locations are amortized using the straight-line method over the shorter of the lease term (including renewal terms) or the estimated useful life of the asset. The cost and accumulated depreciation of assets sold or otherwise disposed of are removed from the accounts and any gain or loss thereon is included in other income and expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Internal Use Software
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company capitalizes software development costs incurred during the application development stage related to new software or major enhancements to the functionality of existing software that is developed solely to meet the Company&#x2019;s internal operational needs and when there are no plans to market the software externally. Costs capitalized include external direct costs of materials and services and internal payroll and payroll-related costs. Any costs during the preliminary project stage or related to training or maintenance are expensed as incurred. Capitalization ceases when the software project is substantially complete and ready for its intended use. The capitalization and ongoing assessment of recoverability of development costs requires considerable judgment by management with respect to certain external factors, including, but not limited to, technological and economic feasibility, and estimated economic life. As of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015

	, &nbsp;

	$0.4

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was included in computer equipment and software
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively
</FONT>

	. The majority of the costs capitalized relate to amounts invoiced by external consultants.&nbsp;The costs are amortized over estimated useful lives of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Leases
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company leases its store and corporate headquarters locations. Assets held under capital leases are included in property, plant and equipment and amortization is included in depreciation expense. Operating lease rentals are expensed on a straight-line basis over the life of the lease beginning on the date the Company takes possession of the property. Tenant improvement allowances are amounts received from a lessor for improvements to leased properties and are amortized against rent expense over the life of the respective leases. At lease inception, the Company determines the lease term by assuming the exercise of those renewal options that are
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>

	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	reasonably assured. The exercise of lease renewal options is at the Company&#x2019;s sole discretion. The lease term is used to determine whether a lease is capital or operating and is used to calculate straight-line rent expense. Additionally, the depreciable life of leased assets and leasehold improvements is limited by the expected lease term. Rent expense is included in

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Self-Insurance
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company is self-insured for certain employee health benefit and workers compensation claims. The Company estimates a liability for aggregate losses below stop-loss coverage limits based on estimates of the ultimate costs to be incurred to settle known claims and claims not reported as of the balance sheet date. The estimated liability is not discounted and is based on a number of assumptions and factors including historical trends, and economic conditions. As of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

	million and
</FONT>

	$0.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million related to estimated employee health benefit claims was included in other current liabilities, respectively. As of December 31,
</FONT>

	2016

	and

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	New Accounting Pronouncements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Recently Adopted Accounting Pronouncements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In August 2014, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	issued a standard requiring an entity&#x2019;s management to evaluate whether there is substantial doubt about an entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year after the date of the financial statements. The guidance also sets forth a series of disclosures that are required in the event the entity&#x2019;s management concludes that there is substantial doubt about the entity&#x2019;s ability to continue as a going concern. The adoption of this new standard did n
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ot have a material effect on the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In February 2015, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	FASB
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	issued a new accounting standard that modif
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ies
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	current consolidation guidance. The standard makes changes to both the variable interest entity model and the voting interest entity model, including modifying the evaluation of whether limited partnerships or similar legal entities are variable interest entities or voting interest entities and amending the guidance for assessing how relationships of related parties affect the consolidation analysis of variable interest entities. The standard was effective
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as of the beginning of fiscal 2016. The adoption of this new standard did not have a material effect on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In April 2015, the FASB issued a standard that requires debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the Consolidated Balance Sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	adopted the provisions of this
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	statement in the first quarter of 2016 and prior periods have been retrospectively adjusted.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption of this standard resulted in a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million reduction of other current assets, net, a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million reduction of other assets, a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million reduction of the current portion of long
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	term debt, and a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million reduction of long
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	term debt in the Consolidated Balance Sheet for the period ended December 31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In March 2016, the FASB issued a standard that amends and simplifies the accounting for stock compensation. The guidance addresses various stock compensation aspects including accounting for income taxes, classification of excess tax benefits on the statement of cash flows, forfeitures, minimum statutory tax withholding requirements, and classification of employee taxes paid on the statement of cash flows when an employer withholds shares for tax withholding purposes, among other things. In order to simplify the accounting for stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	based
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	compensation, the Company made a change in accounting policy to account for forfeitures when they occur, and as a result, we recognized a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million cumulative-effect reduction to retained earnings under the modified retrospective approach. During the third quarter of 2016, the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	recognized an adjustment to reduce
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	additional paid-in capital
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	share
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	based compensation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	by $0.1 million to account for current year forfeiture activity. We elected prospective transition for the requirement to classify excess tax benefits as an operating activity in the Consolidated Statement of Cash Flows. The adoption did not have a material impact on the amounts reported in the Consolidated Statement of Cash Flows for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	year ended December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Additionally,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	will prospectively recognize all excess tax benefits and tax deficiencies as income tax expense or benefit in the Consolidated Statement of Operations as a discrete item in the period in which awards vest. The adoption did not have a material impact on the amounts reported in the Consolidated Statement of Operations for the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	year ended December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	applied the modified retrospective method to recognize the cumulative effect of previously unrecognized excess tax benefits in opening retained earnings.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption did not have a material impact on the amounts reported in the Consolidated Balance Sheet for the year ended December 31, 2015.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	also retrospectively applied the requirement to present employee taxes paid
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	70
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#TTS-20161231X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Table Of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Tile Shop Holdings, Inc. and Subsidiaries
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	when an employer withholds shares for tax-withholding purposes as a financing activity in the Consolidated Statement of Cash Flows.&nbsp;&nbsp;The adoption did not have a material impact on the amounts reported in the Consolidated Statement of Cash Flows for the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	years
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ended
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	31
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 2016 and 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#xFEFF;Accounting Pronouncements Not Yet Adopted
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In May 2014, the FASB issued a final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. This new standard introduces a comprehensive revenue recognition model that requires a company to recognize revenue to depict the transfer of goods or services to a customer at an amount that reflects the consideration it expects to receiv
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e in exchange for those goods or
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ser
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	vices.&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2016, the FASB issued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	several amendments to the standard, including principal versus agent considerations when another party is involved in providing goods or services to a customer, the application of identifying performance obligations, and the recognition of expected breakage amounts either proportionally in earnings as redemptions occur or whe
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	n redemption is remote.&nbsp;&nbsp;T
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	he Company continues to assess the impacts of this standard,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	including evaluating if
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	its current polices to account for samples, gift cards, and sales returns will change under the new standard.&nbsp;&nbsp;As the Company finalizes its assessment, the Company will take steps to define its accounting policies under the new standard, establish new processes and controls when warranted, and ensure these processes are designed to capture the information necessary to conform to the transitional disclosure requirements.&nbsp;&nbsp;The standard is effective for the Company in fiscal 2018 and provides for either full retrospective adoption or modified retrospective adoption by which the cumulative effect of the change is recognized in retained earnings at the date of initial application.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has elected to adopt this standard using the modified retrospective approach.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In July 2015, the FASB issued a standard which simplifies the subsequent measurement of inventory. Currently, an entity is required to measure inventory at the lower of cost or market, whereby market can be replacement cost, net realizable value, or net realizable value less an approximately normal profit margin. The changes require that inventory be measured at the lower of cost and net realizable value, thereby eliminating the use of the other two market methodologies. Net realizable value is defined as the estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business less reasonably predictable costs of completion, disposal, and transportation. These changes become effective for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in fiscal 2017.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	currently assessing the effect the new standard will have on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	its
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In February 2016, the FASB issued a standard that primarily requires organizations that lease assets to recognize the rights and obligations created by those leases on the Consolidated Balance Sheet.&nbsp;&nbsp;The standard is effective in 2019, with early adoption permitted.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	currently assessing the effect the new standard will have on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	its
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In August 2016, the FASB issued an accounting standards update with new guidance on how certain cash receipts and cash payments are presented and classified in the statement of cash flows. The amendments in the standards update provide guidance on eight specific cash flow issues. The standards update is effective retrospectively for fiscal years and interim periods beginning after December 15, 2017, with early adoption permitted.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	currently assessing the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	effect the new standard will have on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	its
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	November
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016, the FASB issued new guidance on restricted cash on the statement of cash flows. The new guidance requires the classification and presentation of changes in restricted cash and cash equivalents in the statement of cash flows. Therefore, amounts generally described as restricted cash and restricted cash equivalents should be included with cash and cash equivalents when reconciling the beginning and ending balances shown on the statement of cash flows. The new standard is effective for fiscal years, and interim periods within those fiscal years, beginning after December 15, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The guidance should be applied retrospectively after adoption.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Restricted cash and long-term restricted cash balances were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$3.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million and $3.9 million, respectively, as of December 31, 2016. Upon adopting the new standard, the Company anticipates that the fluctuations in the restricted cash and long-term restricted cash balances will impact its statement of cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	71
</FONT>

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On June 2, 2015, the Company and its operating subsidiary, The Tile Shop, LLC, entered into a credit agreement with Fifth Third Bank, Bank of America, N.A., and Huntington National Bank (
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as amended,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;).
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 2016, the Credit Agreement was amended to permit an additional New Markets Tax Credit Financing arrangement and on February
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, 2017, the Credit Agreement was amended to permit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to make certain dividend payments.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Credit Agreement provides the Company with a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$125.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million senior secured credit facility, comprised of a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	five
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	-year
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$50.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million term loan and a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$75.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million revolving line of credit. The Credit Agreement is secured by virtually all of the assets of the Company, including but not limited to, inventory, receivables, equipment and real property. Borrowings pursuant to the Credit Agreement bear interest at either a base rate or a LIBOR-based rate, at the option of the Company. The LIBOR-based rate will range from LIBOR plus
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2.00%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, depending on The Tile Shop&#x2019;s leverage ratio. The base rate is equal to the greatest of: (a) the Federal funds rate plus
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0.50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, (b) the Fifth Third Bank &#x201C;prime rate,&#x201D; and (c) the Eurodollar rate plus
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.00%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, in each case plus
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	0.50%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	1.00%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	depending on The Tile Shop&#x2019;s leverage ratio. At December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the base interest rate was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	4.25%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and the LIBOR-based interest rate was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2.27%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Borrowings outstanding consisted of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$10.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million on the revolving line of credit and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$17.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million on the term loan as of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$65.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million available for borrowing on the revolving line of credit as of December 31,

	. &nbsp;

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$1.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million of debt issuance costs in connection with the Credit Agreement. These costs were capitalized as other current and other noncurrent assets, and will be amortized over the

	five

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Credit Agreement contains customary events of default, conditions to borrowings, and restrictive covenants, including restrictions on the Company&#x2019;s ability to dispose of assets, make acquisitions, incur additional debt, incur liens, make investments, or enter into transactions with affiliates on other than terms that could be obtained in an arm&#x2019;s length transaction. The Credit Agreement also includes financial and other covenants including covenants to maintain certain fixed charge coverage ratios and rent adjusted leverage ratios. The Company was in compliance with the covenants as of December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Credit Agreement superseded and replaced in its entirety the Company&#x2019;s senior secured credit facility with Bank of America, N.A. dated October 3, 2012, as amended on April 30, 2013, July 8, 2013, March 26, 2014 and September 29, 2014. The Company used the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$50.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million term loan and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$23.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million drawn on the line of credit pursuant to the Credit Agreement to refinance all of the existing indebtedness outstanding under the Company&#x2019;s prior credit facility in the amount of approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$73.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, which consisted of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$72.8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in unpaid principal and approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in accrued and unpaid interest and fees. The Company also recorded a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million charge in interest expense to write-off of the unamortized deferred financing fees associated with the October 3, 2012 credit facility as of the date of the termination.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 5: Commitments and Contingencies
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Operating leases:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company leases buildings and office space under various operating lease agreements. In addition to rent, most leases require payments of real estate taxes, insurance, and common area maintenance. The leases generally have an initial lease term of ten to fifteen years and contain renewal options and escalation clauses. For leases that contain fixed escalation of the minimum rent or rent holidays, rent expense is recognized on a straight-line basis through the end of the lease term including assumed renewals. The difference between the straight-line rent amounts and amounts payable under the leases is recorded as deferred rent. For the years ended December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, rent expense was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$29.7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$27.2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$25.2
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, respectively.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Annual minimum rentals under non-cancelable operating leases are as follows, for the years ended December 31 (in thousands):
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Legal proceedings:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 507.95PT 0PT 0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of its former executive officers,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of its outside directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of its former directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and certain companies affiliated with the directors, are defendants in a consolidated class action brought under the federal securities laws and now pending in the United States District Court for the District of Minnesota under the caption Beaver County Employees&#x2019; Retirement Fund, et al. v. Tile Shop Holdings, Inc., et al. Several related actions were filed in 2013 and subsequently consolidated. The plaintiffs are
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	investors who represent classes consisting of (1) all purchasers of Tile Shop common stock between August 22, 2012 and January 28, 2014 (the &#x201C;class period&#x201D;), seeking to pursue remedies under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934; and (2) all purchasers of Tile Shop common stock pursuant and/or traceable to the Company&#x2019;s December 2012 registration statement, seeking to pursue remedies under the Securities Act of 1933.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	firms who were underwriters in the December 2012 secondary public offering are also named as defendants.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plaintiffs allege that during the class period, defendants failed to disclose certain related party transactions in the Company&#x2019;s SEC filings and press releases.&nbsp;&nbsp;The plaintiffs assert claims under Sections 11, 12(a)(2), and 15 of the Securities Act of 1933, and under Sections 10(b) and 20(a) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934. In addition to attorneys&#x2019; fees and costs, the plaintiffs seek to recover damages on behalf of class members.&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Subsequent to December 31, 2016, t
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	he parties have entered into a Stipulation of Settlement
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	(&#x201C;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	S
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tipulation&#x201D;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	dated January 13, 2017 to settle all claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pursuant to the Stipulation,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$9.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million will be paid on behalf of all defendants.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company has agreed to pay
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$5.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million of that amount and the insurance company providing coverage for the initial tier of the Company&#x2019;s directors and officer&#x2019;s policy has agreed to pay
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$4.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million of the settlement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company and the insurance provider subsequently transferred money to an escrow account that had been
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	established to hold the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>

	Tile Shop Holdings, Inc. and Subsidiaries
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	settlement fund.&nbsp;&nbsp;The settlement is subject to court approval.&nbsp;&nbsp;The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	c
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ourt has scheduled a hearing on whether to grant final approval of the settlement for May 3, 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The net charge of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$5.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million was recorded in selling, general and administrative
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	expenses
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in the Consolidated Statement of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Operations during the year ended
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	December 31, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company recorded a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$9.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million other current liability and a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$4.5
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million other current asset in the Consolidated Balance Sheet as of December 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to reflect the Company&#x2019;s obligation to the class and the corresponding receivable from the insurance company
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company will pursue recovery of this amount as well as other legal fees incurred in connection with this case from its insurance providers who cover losses under the directors and offers policy exceeding the initial tier of coverage.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company also is a Defendant in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	actions brought derivatively on behalf of the Company by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shareholders in the Court of Chancery for the State of Delaware (&#x201C;Delaware Chancery Court&#x201D;).
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of the actions were filed in 2015 and then consolidated (the &#x201C;Consolidated Actions&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On July 31, 2015, the plaintiff-shareholders in the Consolidated Actions filed a consolidated complaint. The consolidated complaint names as defendants
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	current
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	members of the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of its former Directors,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	former employee of the Company. The third action (the &#x201C;Third Action&#x201D;) was filed on or about September 28, 2016 against
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	seven
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	members of the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	former officer, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	former employee.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All of the complaints track many of the same factual allegations as have been made in the above-described federal securities class action. They allege that the defendant-directors and/or officer breached their fiduciary duties by failing to adopt adequate internal controls for the Company, by approving false and misleading statements issued by the Company, by causing the Company to violate generally accepted accounting principles and SEC regulations, by engaging in or approving alleged insider trading, and by permitting the Company&#x2019;s primary product to contain illegal amounts of lead. The complaints also allege claims for insider trading and/or unjust enrichment. The complaints seek damages, disgorgement, an award of attorneys&#x2019; fees and other expenses, and an order compelling changes to the Company&#x2019;s corporate governance and internal procedures. In 2015, the defendants moved to dismiss the Consolidated Actions, or in the alternative, to stay the Consolidated Actions pending resolution of the Beaver County Employees&#x2019; Retirement Fund action described above.&nbsp;&nbsp;Subsequently, upon agreement of the parties, the Court entered an Order staying the Consolidated Actions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Recently the Company moved to dismiss the newly-filed Third Action, or in the alternative, to stay the Third Action until resolution of the Beaver County Employees&#x2019; Retirement Fund action described above, or until the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	takes action on the demand described below.&nbsp;&nbsp;That motion has not yet been decided.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	By letter dated May 19, 2016, a shareholder of the Company, through his attorney and prior to filing the Third Action, demanded that the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	investigate alleged breaches of fiduciary duty related to the same matters described above, and take action against certain present and former officers and directors of the Company. The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	has appointed a committee of two independent directors to investigate and evaluate the matters raised in the demand letter, and to recommend to the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	what actions, if any should be taken by the Company with respect to the matters raised in the demand letter.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Given the uncertainty of litigation and the preliminary stage of these cases, the Company cannot reasonably estimate the possible loss or range of loss that may result from these actions. The Company maintains directors and officers liability insurance policies that may reduce the Company&#x2019;s exposure, if any. In the event the Company incurs a loss, the Company will pursue recoveries to the maximum extent available under these policies.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company is also, from time to time, subject to claims and disputes arising in the normal course of business.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the opinion of management, while the outcome of such claims and disputes cannot be predicted with certainty, the Company&#x2019;s ultimate liability in connection with these matters is not expected to have a material adverse effect on the results of operations, financial position, or cash flows.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 6: Fair Value of Financial Instruments:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Fair value is the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (an exit price) in the principal or most advantageous market for the asset or liability in an orderly transaction between market participants on the measurement date. To measure fair value, the Company uses a three-tier valuation hierarchy based upon observable and non-observable inputs:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 27PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Level 1 &#x2013; Unadjusted quoted prices that are available in active markets for the identical assets or liabilities at the measurement date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 27PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Level 2 &#x2013; Significant other observable inputs available at the measurement date, other than quoted prices included in Level 1, either directly or indirectly, including:
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:36PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="WIDTH: 18.00PT; DISPLAY: INLINE;">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:5PT 0PT 0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:5PT 0PT 0PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;WIDTH:0PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:5PT 0PT 0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Quoted prices for similar assets or liabilities in active markets;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH:100%;" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0">

</P>

<FONT STYLE="MARGIN:5PT 0PT 0PT;FONT-FAMILY:SYMBOL;FONT-SIZE:8PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;;">
	&#xB7;
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;">
<P STYLE="WIDTH:0PT;WIDTH:0PT;FONT-SIZE:0PT;">
</P>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;MARGIN:5PT 0PT 0PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Quoted prices for identical or similar assets
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	or liabilities

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	in non-active markets;

</TD>

	2016,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	and 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Note 8: Earnings Per Share
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Basic earnings per share is cal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	culated by dividing net income
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	by the weighted-average number of shares outstanding during the period. Diluted earnings per share is cal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	culated by dividing net income
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding, after taking into consideration all dilutive potential common shares outstanding during the period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	76
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 2.7PT 0PT 0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 9: Equity Incentive Plans
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	2012 Plan:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Under the 2012 Omnibus Award Plan (the &#x201C;2012 Plan&#x201D;),
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2,500,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock were initially reserved for issuance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	pursuant to a variety of stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	based compensation awards, including stock options, and restricted stock awards. The number of shares initially reserved for issuance or transfer pursuant to awards under the 2012 Plan was to be increased on the first day of each calendar year beginning in 2013 and ending in 2022, in an amount equal to the lesser of (A)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2,500,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shares, (B)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	percent (6%) of the shares of common stock outstanding (on an as-converted basis) on the last day of the immediately preceding calendar year, and (C) such smaller number of shares of stock as determined by the Company&#x2019;s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Board of Directors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. During 2013, (i) 2,500,000 shares of common stock were added to the 2012 Plan reserve effective January 1, 2013 in accordance with the automatic share increase provision of the 2012 Plan, (ii) the 2012 Plan was amended to eliminate the automatic share increase for subsequent years, and (iii) the 2012 Plan was amended to authorize grants of performance-based awards, which may be paid in cash or equity. The amendments to the 2012 Plan were approved by the Company&#x2019;s stockholders in July 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Stock Options:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	During the years ended December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, the Company granted stock options to its employees that included service condition requirements. The options provide for certain acceleration of vesting and cancellation of options under different circumstances, such as a change in control, death, disability and termination of service. The Company recogniz
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	es compensation expense
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	on a straight-line basis over the requisite service period
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, net of actual forfeitures
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. For the portion of the options that contain both a market and service condition, the Company recognizes compensation expense, net of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	actual
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	forfeitures, using graded vesting over the requisite service period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The fair value of each option grant was estimated on the date of grant using the Black-Scholes option pricing model. The assumptions used in the option valuation models are outlined in the following table:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The computation of the expected volatility assumptions used in the option valuation models was based on historical volatilities of the Company. The Company used the &#x201C;simplified&#x201D; method for an expected life as prescribed in SEC Staff Accounting Bulletin (&#x201C;SAB&#x201D;) No. 110, for companies that do not have adequate historical data. The risk-free interest rate was based on the U.S. Treasury yield at the time of grant.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The expected dividend yield was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	zero
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	for all stock options granted prior to December 31, 2016 based on the fact that
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, at that time,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the Company had not paid dividend
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	or a plan
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to pay dividend
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in the future.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	To the extent that actual outcomes differ from the Company's assumptions, the Company is not required to true up grant-date fair value-based expense to final intrinsic values. The weighted average fair value of stock options granted was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$7.37
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;

</FONT>

	during the years ended December 31,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, &nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>

	2014

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, respectively.

	The aggregate intrinsic value is the difference between the exercise price and the closing price of the Company&#x2019;s stock on December 31. The intrinsic value of the stock options exercised during
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$0.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Tile Shop, LLC tax returns for periods 2010 through the Business Combination on August 21, 2012 are subject to examination by the IRS
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	however, these tax liabilities are the responsibility of the former The Tile Shop members.&nbsp; The Company&#x2019;s federal and state tax returns for the periods ended December 31, 2013, December 31, 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and December 31, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	remain subject to examination.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The Company has not recorded U.S. deferred income taxes on approximately $0.5 million of its non-U.S. subsidiaries' undistributed earnings because such amounts are intended to be reinvested outside the United States indefinitely. If these earnings were repatriated to the United States, the Company would be required to accrue and pay U.S. federal income taxes and foreign withholding taxes, as adjusted for foreign tax credits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;LINE-HEIGHT:100%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 1PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:1PT;">
	&#xFEFF;
